Let me ask about some other people.
Tiger Teague, was he a good ally for A&M?
What did he work hardest for, for A&M?
What about Lupo, old Army Lou?
Lupo that ran the store at Northgate,
he was a classmate of Mr. Rutter and Mr. Teague's,
and he loaned money to students always.
I remember him as a, when I got there,
he was a kind of a frail little man,
but always had a smile and had lots of energy
and was always going around shaking hands
and patting people on the back.
Mr. Zachary, as a, I know he was a classmate.
When he was on the board,
was he a strong supporter of change?
Oh, he was not for coeducation,
but he did care about A&M very deeply.
that his son may soon be appointed to the board.
We talked about Buck Shewitch yesterday.
was he large in weight as he would later be,
or was he kind of trim?
And did, was he a pleasant,
No, he was a good kid.
He was a great, good kid.
Oh, he was a great kid.
He was a great, great guy.
He was a very good guy.
One of the best friends I have.
If you ever decide you want to sell any of your Shewitch items,
I want to bid for them,
because my wife and I knew him,
Buck was such a special guy.
Tom Harrington, you knew him as a student.
What kind of student was he?
What kind of student was he?
My earliest years, we lived in Garland,
and when we needed anything fixed on the Farmall tractor,
we went to Plano because the Harrington family owned that,
and I believe a funeral home, and I think a furniture store.
And the Harrington family was very, very good.
As time came to consider co-education and volunteer core,
was Dr. Harrington supportive of those changes?
I hadn't thought about that, that he would have to follow the board.
Dick Hervey, as executive director of the former students,
was he a strong advocate for A&M?
Because you and Dick worked closely together, didn't you?
The former student association has been very blessed
to have such good leadership, and now with Randy Mattson.
I met him the day that John Lindsay brought him to A&M
to try to recruit him as a student.
Oh, in high school, he was All-State.
Then he played one year of basketball at A&M
Basically, he's a good, solid human being.
What did you learn from that experience?
What did being in the Corps teach you?
To be on time, I guess.
Describe the uniforms that you all wore when you were a student.
What did the uniforms look like then, the student uniforms?
Was it a gray shirt then?
Did you all wear the high senior boots?
Did you... Did you call your roommates Fish-O-Ladies then?
Did you all have a lot of slang?
Do you remember any of it?
Did the teachers, the faculty members, have nicknames then?
I came to Pitt's course, cleaning up the bar.
Now, what were your favorite courses?
What subjects did you most enjoy?
When you make a hundred, then you did.
What were the hardest courses for you?
The ones that you had to work the hardest.

Did he teach any courses then in English?

Dana Bible, the coach, the star of the football team?
Coach Dana X. Bible was the football coach,
but I don't remember who the basketball coach was.
Did I ask you if you knew Hiney Weir?
He later taught at Shriner in Kerrville.
But he wasn't as big as Weir, was he?
Was Gill a good football player?
Was Coach Bible an excellent coach?
Did he relate well to students?
Because to me, the 12th man story revolves around him.
Whether it's a legend or a fact, it still relates around him.

Did anybody ever get into biscuit fights and throw biscuits?

Did the sophomores do the paddling or the seniors?

Do you want to stimulate that?
See, I think that's good proof that the good works of people can live a long, long time.

to say that I have an acquaintance with you.

So an indoor swimming pool, pool hall.

They'd beat the hell out of you for a freshman.
Now, you graduated in four years.

Did General Pershing, by chance, did he come?
Guyon Hall was the big assembly room.
Did you all have worship services in there?
And who would lead the service?
Was there a chaplain for the...
Did you all have a religious emphasis week?
In the 1950s, there was religious emphasis week.
Did you go to church while you were a student?
Had you been a church member before you went away?
So you were fully immersed and washed clean.
Were there any tragic events that happened to any of your friends while you were at A&M?
Most of your friends, were they from the city, or were they from small towns?
